   1.🥰CPU-I/O Burst Cycle | CPU Bound Process | I/O Bound Process | Operating Systems | Input Output| OS

        🧠 CPU–I/O Burst Cycle

           A process execution consists of alternating:
           
           CPU bursts → doing computations
           I/O bursts → waiting for input/output
           
           👉 The cycle repeats until the process finishes.


        🧠 CPU-Bound Process
            Spends more time in CPU bursts
            Very little I/O
            
            👉 Example: calculations, data processing   

        🧠 I/O-Bound Process
            Spends more time in I/O bursts
            Less CPU work
            
            👉 Example: file reading, user input tasks  

  2.😎 Preemptive Scheduling | Non Preemptive Scheduling | CPU scheduler | Short Term Scheduler | OS 
  
        🧠 CPU Scheduler / Short-Term Scheduler

              The CPU scheduler (also called short-term scheduler) selects a process from the ready queue and allocates the CPU.


        🧠 Preemptive Scheduling
             CPU can be taken away from a running process
             OS can switch to another process anytime
             
             👉 Example: Round Robin    

        🧠 Non-Preemptive Scheduling
             Once a process gets CPU, it runs until completion or waiting
             No interruption
             
             👉 Example: FCFS       
              
        